@PubliusAmerica2 It certainly is a trend that will not spontaneously reverse itself. Whether there is necessarily only one way to effect a reversal remains to be seen. I am willing to try almost anything short of revolution *first* (surrender being ultimately out of the question, of course).

@sometherapist In a very real way, Racism is practically non-existent in America; not wholly absent in every possible way, but an extreme outlier in terms of common behavior across all levels of society.

@Ravie777 On that note, I think we have both expressed enough for the other to ponder over for the moment. I must be in about other tasks. Thanks again for challenging me to express myself more clearly under challenge. https://t.co/6R6rffbaQz

@Ravie777 I also agree with abolishing farm subsidies. All subsidies; to persons or businesses. No welfare for anyone, not single mothers and not corporations. I would also abolish every last Alphabet Agency at the federal level (DEA, FBI, CIA, EPA, etc.; all of them, bar none).

@Ravie777 Not necessarily, but even if we accept that framing I believe the societal consequences are infinitely worse in allowing single motherhood to proliferate; consequences that extend far beyond the limited scope of only "suffering children" and inflict greater harm on everyone.

@Ravie777 Sadly, it has been the result of free choice that these high-sugar products have succeeded on the market. An effective component of social stigma ought also be directed against the purchase of such foods. If no one buys them, they stop being sold.
@Ravie777 I accept that we disagree. I also laud your desire to alleviate suffering, and to avoid causing unnecessary suffering. We completely agree in those desired outcomes.

@Ravie777 I might personally choose to do so. I would use that opportunity to discuss their life w/ them, toward the purpose of identifying mistakes which caused their wretched condition. This may include helping them understand they are suffering because their mother made a bad decision.

@Ravie777 The modern welfare state ought be abolished in total & natural consequences be allowed to solve the problem. Nothing will change so long as government handouts enable poor choices, & our civilization will continue to decline as ever more people are incentivized to choose poorly.

@Ravie777 They may not like it, but they choose it. There is no other cause. We have acted to alleviate the natural shame of being fat rather than advocating shame as an appropriate emotion one ought experience for being fat. Thus, obesity increases as more excuses are made.

@Ravie777 The solution *is* broad social stigma. Every individual (and ONLY every individual) can enact effective remedy, exclusively on the personal level. There is no other cure for this problem. Externalizing the locus of control only serves to exacerbate the problem.

@Ravie777 If we accept that harm will attend I  either case (and it will), the only acceptable harm is that found in natural consequences which result from individual's own poor decisions. Attempts to "social engineer" away natural consequences can only be a disaster.

@Ravie777 I believe it is precisely the opposite. By mitigating natural consequences we have effectively encouraged the bad decisions to proliferate. I do not advocate inflicting additional harm, that would be unconscionable, but that we stop mitigating consequences & allow it to resolve.

@Ravie777 The anti-"fat shaming" movement and media pushing "healthy at any size" beg to differ. These things would not be possible without improper tolerance for unhealthy behavior. It is no longer stigmatized as strongly as it once was, and it grows worse as that stigma further fades.
@Ravie777 Why would you seek to externalize the locus of control over one's own health and fitness? It is not possible that anyone else is to blame *but* the individual and their choices.

@Ravie777 Harm to children is one small subset. There is more harm to society at large, to the people who live in that society (including children) obtained by failing to condemn bad choices. These bad choices become more likely as society mitigates the natural consequences which result.

@Ravie777 It is caused exclusively by my own choices. I endorse the Oppose position, as with single motherhood. This means the broader public ought vocally denounce that choice as objectively inferior and withhold sympathy or accommodation for the natural consequences which attend.

@Ravie777 Consider that we have merely swapped out one set of dire consequences for another. It is possible that the problems generated by single motherhood and fatherless homes are infinitely worse than the social stigma under which some women chose infanticide.

@Ravie777 It is worth considering that we ought passively allow single mothers & their children to suffer as an object lesson to everyone else that such choices have consequences. I wish them no harm, but the alternative appears to be worse. Mitigating consequences encourages behavior.

@Ravie777 Being fat is a perfect example. I *am fat; verweight to an unhealthy degree. I denounce living in this state & recommend against it. I do not consider it merely coequal to being thin & healthy. I accept & endorse this condemnation in the hope that others will choose otherwise.

@Ravie777 Basically, we tried being "kind" to avoid hurting the feelings of people who made an obviously bad decision, and the result has been an increase in the number of people making bad decisions. It appears we must return to vocal and firm condemnation to reverse the trend.

@Ravie777 The question then remains: why the massive increase in single motherhood in the past 70-80 years. I link this directly to the decline in social stigma against single motherhood itself. Nothing else reasonably explains the phenomena.

@Ravie777 Actions speak louder than Words. If indeed everyone agreed, we would see everyone act out that behavior. The problem itself *is* the extant lack of agreement. I don't avoid murder because of feared imprisonment, but because I believe it is wrong. I act as I believe. So do we all.

@Ravie777 It seems self-evident that we will enact the morals we are raised to believe. As such, we must actually *teach* those morals (speak them) if we expect people to act them out. This requires starting them explicitly, as well as explaining the consequences which may be avoided.

@Ravie777 I believe heroin use is genuinely Opposed in the broader culture to a degree much more significant than expressed opposition to single-motherhood. It appears this attitude has changed since 1950/60 to be more broadly accepting of single motherhood as a merely coequal outcome.
@Ravie777 Unfortunately, my poll is no valid measure, for the reasons stated. At most, it fails to demonstrate my assertion. It does not prove the opposite assertion is necessarily true.
@Ravie777 I believe it can be. I understand if you disagree.

@Ravie777 I agree. Thus "empty words" will need to suffice. Consider: a friend asks if she should have a baby alone or with a husband under marriage. What do you tell her? Do you say both conditions are merely equal, and one is not better than the other?

@Ravie777 I believe it is a necessary first step that we publicly denounce single motherhood as objectively inferior, else we can never solve the problem of fatherless homes. What people believe informs how they behave. It must be universally understood as a bad outcome first.

@Ravie777 Please also note that by identifying it as a "problem" you are yourself offering moral condemnation, and doing so publicly on social media. You are effectively enacting my advocated position of Opposition, rather than Support or Neutrality.
@Ravie777 Do you prefer that such "empty words" be backed by some specific action? Is your only complaint that more is not being actively done to punish or ostracize people who make such mistakes?

@Ravie777 We simply disagree over whether broad, public "moral condemnation" *is* pointless. We also disagree over whether "everybody knows" that these things *are* immoral (or produce negative consequences inferior to the alternative). I'm not sure how to reconcile these divergent views.

@Ravie777 @PublicShawnelle You may be struggling with the concept that merely speaking the truth has inherent value, independent of whether that accomplishes any specific outcome. I believe doing so *does* effect outcomes, but this is not a necessary condition to endorse "speaking the truth" itself.

@Ravie777 @PublicShawnelle Are you parsing "empty words" from "taking action" as separate things? Sometimes words are enough to effect social pressure. Sometimes actions must comport to enforce those words. Failing to "walk the talk" may indeed be insufficient to produce desired outcomes.

@Ravie777 @PublicShawnelle I'm not sure this is the case at all. Perhaps many people privately acknowledge this fact, but how many actually state it out loud and assert it as a moral truth that ought be obeyed? You may be a case in point. You hesitate to advocate this truth, thinking it pointless to do so.

@Ravie777 @PublicShawnelle That said, I believe it is worse to minimize the mistake & forgo accurately identifying the behavior *as* a mistake for the sake of preventing "hurt feelings." This applies at the personal level to avoid repeating the mistake, & as social object lessons for negative outcomes.

@Ravie777 @PublicShawnelle To steelman the argument for compassion, there is validity to the idea of "making a bad situation worse" by piling-on or "rubbing it in" when a mistake has occurred. Granted, this can seem emotionally cruel. It is legitimately important to NOT seek exacerbation of distress.

@Ravie777 @PublicShawnelle To the matter of behavioral change by social pressure, we have 3 options: 1) Support; 2) Opposition; and, 3) Neutrality. The only course of action which might hope to reduce teen pregnancy is Opposition. Support and Neutrality only serve to ignore or exacerbate the problem.

@Ravie777 @PublicShawnelle I believe social pressure can accomplish behavioral change, but that this metric is irrelevant. The issue of whether or not a thing is objectively superior or inferior in comparison to an alternative is wholly separate from whether public acknowledgement has any specific effect.

I still believe my original assertion is accurate, though I am unsure how to best demonstrate the phenomena in question; specifically, the apparent likelihood that persons who do so advocate face significant opposition, and even risk social media censorship for TOS violation.

Potential Confounds: 1) low sample size (10); 2) question as phrased was not composed in a manner capable of rendering a relevant result; 3) non-representative sample (poll did not reach/include those most likely to select Disagree or Bigot options to demonstrate initial claim).

What we have in the Greek conception of Zeus, in specific reference to the above graphic, is the human traits of both a capacity for producing offspring & the seemingly irrational or capricious desire to do so; with the potential that these offspring may become Gods or Monsters! https://t.co/9cI5KqNgwV

Thus being the "creator" of the Greek Pantheon (setting aside his co-equal siblings and apparent incest with his sister/wife, Hera), Zeus is conceived to be the progenitor of both demigod Heroes and a fair number of Monsters (perhaps the most famous being the Minotaur of Crete). https://t.co/2lLkAP1bor

Zeus was conceived as the offspring of Chronos (Time) & Gaia (Space). Thus, he stands as the Icon of the Human Experience; beings existing in a Temporal & Physical reality. He also stands as the iconic Progenitor (from "gen" meaning birth or origin): thus, "Father of The Gods." https://t.co/DNtOaoosYL

So, to properly understand why the graphic which opened this thread is both humorous and insightful, we must ask: "What are the human Traits (Powers *and* Flaws) attributed to Zeus, and what are these attributes meant to teach us about ourselves?" https://t.co/S0eO5TWpjH

Remember, these are all man-made stories, made for the sake of mankind; they tell *our* story, & these Gods *must* have human traits that explain us *to* ourselves. All of this to (finally!) bring us back  to Zeus with the knowledge that he was also conceived to be as "flawed" as his fellow Gods. The important factor is that everything a God did was powerful or had an effect in the world, not that this effect was always Wise, Just, or Good. https://t.co/OsLVjX2dJN

In brief, Greeks conceived their Gods to be powerful, but not entirely perfect nor necessarily Good; much more human in behavior, & subject to the same human flaws. Thus, the jealousy & anger of Aphrodite in being denied the Golden Apple led to the Trojan War. (Many such cases!) https://t.co/P3DwDWChPd

To best appreciate these Myths, one must know that the Gods were not conceived to be omnipotent nor omniscient, but as the embodiment of Primal Forces. Thus, Love (Aphrodite) and War (Ares): supreme in their specific essence, but otherwise limited outside of that inherent nature. https://t.co/ygOMR2i5MN

That said, do not be mistaken in believing that *all* Heroes did so without consequences; nor even their fellow Gods. A solid Stone Wall is not a Hearth; there must be an open space for the Fire. A Fire *not* contained by Stone is ultimately unfit for purpose; useless, & worse, dangerous. Thus, the "Golden Mean" of balance necessary to provide the safe & effective necessity of heat & light.

A body made entirely of rigid Bone has no ability for motion, nor is a body of pure Muscle as effective and efficient as one with bones against which those muscles may leverage: the "Golden Mean" of Flexibility *and* Rigidity in proper proportion.

All of this (seemingly) endless repetition of the core concept is meant to drive home the point that neither Fire nor Stone are inherently Good or Evil. The proper balance *must* exist between the Fiery Progress of Chaotic Change and the Conservative Stone of Orderly Stability.

It is the Nature of the Purpose itself which precludes excessive Stone that can only choke the Fire & obstruct adequate heat & light, & dictates the Fire not exceed the capacity of the Stone to contain it, such that the Fire itself obliterate any possibility of that useful Goal.

The very Nature of that Purpose itself dictates the Stone which must bound the limits of the Fire such that it both allows adequate heat and light to exist & can *only* serve to achieve that intended Purpose, preventing it from spreading beyond & causing unintended harm.

However the problem is scaled, the analogy to a *useful* fire is sound. We must assume that our purpose is *not* to burn down the entire house in attempting to warm and illuminate the house itself, nor to destroy the neighborhood in seeking to demolish one condemned building.

Not only does the legitimacy of this method depend entirely on the presumption that the existing structure *is* uninhabitable, but that this fire can itself be contained to *only* that specific outcome, & will not rage out of control to destroy other useful things in its wake.

To "Steel Man" the argument of those who would advocate "Demolition by Fire," I acknowledge it to be an efficient & effective method for the purpose of most quickly & completely accomplishing that specific purpose. However, this method entails the risk of unintended consequences.

Of course, this does presume that our intent is *not* to burn down the house. Sometimes that *is* the Goal, under given circumstances. I would argue it an unacceptably dangerous method for acheiving the demolition of a condemned structure, but that may ultimately be negotiable.

We cannot change the Nature of Fire and Stone; we may only apply their inherent qualities in the context of our desired outcome. The specific Heat & Light we seek dictates the quantity of Wood, which dictates the size and density of the Hearth needed to avoid a house fire.

All things must exist in the precisely "proper proportion" as is made necessary by the chosen Goal, and is not remotely the mere Hegelian "synthesis of opposites" into a muddled, useless absolute Midpoint. What we must seek is the applied Principle of Aristotle's "Golden Mean."

What follows requires both intellectually honest Generosity of Understanding & the ability for Abstraction in Applied Metaphor. 

Yin & Yang.
Fire & Stone.
Muscle & Bone
Chaos & Order.
Change & Stability.
Progressive & Conservative.

It is my belief that only those capable of critical thought, & of comprehending Argument by Analogy, will have evinced the perseverance necessary to reach this point of my explanation. Those who fell by the wayside have selected themselves for incompatibility. Sad, but so be it.

How then, you ask, does this all relate to "Politics," of all things? And why the devil was it necessary for such loquacious digression!?

Fear not; I shall explain!

Again, it is necessary to accept that a Reality exists beyond mere Human Experience. Under proper conditions, Fire burns. This objective fact can't be modified by Human Will: we may only choose When, Where & Why; What it is, & How it functions, are not subject to mere preference.

To draw the most relevant & specific Boundaries on selecting a useful Path, we thus employ the objective knowledge that a Wood-fueled Fire cannot consume Stone, & have the answer to avoiding unintended consequences which would necessarily obstruct our Journey to the Destination.

Here enters another Map, nested w/in the context of the "heat & light in a home" Goal: the Landscape of Stone *in relation* to Fire. The objective Nature of Rock is that it does not "burn." (Again, obfuscant sophists who would reference Lava may kindly exit at this juncture.)

Knowing that Fire *will* consume *all* fuel it contacts, & that our Home is entirely comprised of such fuel, it then becomes necessary to choose a Path on this Map which precludes exposing the Home matrials directly to the Fire, else the home itself be unintentiinally consumed.

By this, we must grant that our Goal is to warm & illuminate a habitable space. It ought be clearly understood that, if we aim for that Destination of "a warm and well-lit home," this presupposes we wish to preserve the Home intact, such that we *have* that space to heat & light.

Our *intended* consequence may be the production of Heat & Light. Given the objective Nature of Fire, we know this will occur under the described conditions. We also know that Fire will consume *all* fuel which it contacts, narrowing the Best Path to *only* warmth & illumination.

The broader Map of Fire necessitates the prerequisites of Spark, Fuel & Oxygen, but allows for a variety of fuel types, spark sources & oxygen mixture. However, the desired Goal will also guide & limit selection among these choices; & this Goal includes attendant consequences.

Once a Map has been selected in terms of the desired Destination, there remain many paths to the same Goal, and many variations of Goal which will determine precisely *how* that Map is used to reach a given selected Goal. The Goal itself necessarily limits how we employ the Map.

Under the contextual Goal of generating Heat or Light, we must use our knowledge of observable Physical Reality, & thus select Fire as the most relevant & useful Map for navigating toward that Destination. As such, the Nature of a Thing reflexively determines it's usefullness.

As such, we must *first* choose a given Destination (or Goal) *before* selecting the Map. Map relevance is generated by nesting it w/in the context of the Destination. Understanding the objective Nature of Fire, *that* Map is broadly useless if our Goal is to chill a beverage.

In applying the concept that "human choice determines relevance," we must beware the fallacy that mere Human Choice may alter Reality itself. The map of Chicago *cannot* be *made* relevant to navigating Baton Rouge by any act of human will; we may *only* choose which map to use.

Such concepts as Relevance & Usefulness are most properly classed as "constructs" in a way that Physical Reality cannot be. As above mentioned, a map of Chicago is Objective and Real, though neither Relevant nor Useul in navigating Baton Rouge. Here, human choice must operate.

"So what if I grant that Fire is Real? What do I care that it *is* a chemical process yielding heat and light? How is this specifically relevant or useful that we have objectively identified these features?"

Again: it depends.

Having accurately & objectively identified the Reality of Fire itself as it exists in Nature, independent of Human Experience (& yet using universal Human Experience to derive the description), we have a Map of the Landscape. What we lack is a Destination to give it Relevance.

(Obfuscators who would quibble that "a deaf man cannot *hear* the tree fall!" may see themselves out of this conversation entirely, as such sophistry is beyond inappropriate & intellectually dishonest. There is no rational or relevant objection to the given description of Fire.)

To borrow the wisdom of Forrest Gump's mama: "Fire *is* what Fire does." Specifically and observably, Fire itself is a chemical reaction in-process, originating from a "spark" added to fuel and oxygen, generating radiated heat and light (and smoke, ash, etc.).

Whether or not Human Experience *is* a necessary condition to establish the Reality of Fire itself, that criteria is satisfied by Human Experience itself: when present, we can & *do* perceive the phenomena of Fire in specific and universal ways, without exception.

Having established the Reality of Fire itself independent of human experience, we are still limited by human experience in making observations & drawing conclusions. This is a philosophically sticky wicket I will elide, and the base reason for using Fire in this analogy.

All this is to say that a given Map has no less Reality simply because it is irrelevant, nor does the Reality itself necessaeily cause universal Relevance in all situations. A map of Chicago is no less real simply because it is useless in aiding navigation through Baton Rouge.

The "No" answer is equally "true," but for a different reason. This answer speaks to a given phenomenon's relevance in terms of impact on human experience. If a tree falls *and* makes a "sound," but no human is present, it has no relevance to that person's experience.

I submit, in practical terms, that "sound" is not a phenomenon which exists only in the perceiving of it by human ears, but is a physical phenomenon of objective reality that exists in the waves of disturbed air caused by the falling tree. Humans may only perceive it or not.

To callback an actual zen koan: "If a tree falls in the forests and no person is around to hear it fall, does it make a sound?" The answer is both Yes *and* No, depending on how one chooses to interpret the idea of "sound." Is sound itself *only* what is perceived by humans?

What are the "geographical" features of Fire itself that draw such a map for us? First, we must accept that "fire" is not merely a concept; it does not exist only because we have given it a name. Fire is a phenomenon that exists as an independent, objective, physical reality.

First, we must do precisely that: Map the Landscape; identify relevant observable features as they exist in reality, & which must be addressed in some way. These "features of reality" can't be ignored; they can't be "wished away," & must inform our choices if we hope to succeed.

Broadly speaking, the reply "That depends," is correct in general, but not at all useful in bridging the Is-Ought divide. What gives us the specific Answer is identifying a specific Goal. A map can only identify the landscape, & better/worse paths; it cannot choose a destination.
